        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">What are the best exercises to prevent muscle loss after 50?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">The best exercises are compound resistance movements that work multiple muscle groups simultaneously: squats, deadlifts, rows, bench or floor press, overhead press, lunges, and farmer's carries. Done 2–3 times per week with progressive overload and adequate protein, these movements reliably halt sarcopenia progression and create conditions for modest muscle gain.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">How often should men over 50 do resistance training?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Research supports 2–3 resistance training sessions per week for men over 50. Each session should include compound movements targeting major muscle groups. Rest days between sessions matter — muscle is built during recovery, not during the workout itself. Two full-body sessions per week is a sustainable and effective starting point.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Can men over 50 build muscle without a gym?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes. Bodyweight exercises — squats, push-ups, lunges, rows using a table or low bar — provide sufficient resistance for muscle preservation and modest gains. The key is progressive overload: consistently increasing difficulty over time through more reps, slower tempo, or harder variations. A gym adds convenience and load options, but isn't required.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Is cardio or strength training better for men over 50?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">For muscle preservation specifically, resistance training is more effective. Cardio supports cardiovascular health and general fitness but does not create the mechanical stimulus needed to maintain muscle mass. The optimal approach combines both — resistance training 2–3 times per week as the priority, with cardio as a complement on other days.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Does exercise alone prevent muscle loss after 50?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Exercise alone is significantly less effective than exercise combined with adequate protein. Research shows that resistance training and protein work synergistically — each amplifies the other. Men who lift but chronically under-eat protein see much slower results than those who combine both. Protein is the raw material; resistance training is the signal to use it.</div>
